@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "OASIS - Free Games Portal";
}

<div class="text-center my-5 py-4">
    <h1 class="display-3 fw-bold text-gradient tracking-tight">Welcome to the OASIS</h1>
    <p class="lead text-muted fs-4 mx-auto" style="max-width: 700px;">
        A clean, fast web portal designed to help you discover free video games.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-4">
        <a asp-page="/GameToFree" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg px-4 py-2 fw-semibold">Find a Random Game</a>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row g-4 mt-2">
    <div class="col-lg-6">
        <div class="main-container h-100">
            <h2 class="h4 mb-3 border-bottom pb-2 text-primary">Why We Chose .NET</h2>
            <p>
                Our team chose Microsoft's <strong>.NET web stack</strong> because it is fast, secure, and highly stable. In our past projects, we used JavaScript setups, but switching to .NET and C# helps us build cleaner code that catches errors before the website even runs.
            </p>
            <p>
                Using C# for the entire backend allows our web application to handle data quickly and smoothly, ensuring the pages load without any delay or lag for the user.
            </p>

            <h3 class="h6 mt-4 mb-2 text-uppercase font-weight-bold text-muted small">System Layout</h3>
            <table class="table table-sm mt-2 table-borderless">
                <tbody>
                    <tr class="border-bottom">
                        <td style="width: 35%;" class="fw-bold">Frontend (Visuals)</td>
                        <td class="text-secondary">Razor Pages Engine, Bootstrap 5, and our custom OASIS color theme</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-bottom">
                        <td class="fw-bold">Backend (Logic)</td>
                        <td class="text-secondary">C# code running on an embedded Kestrel web server pipeline</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-bottom">
                        <td class="fw-bold">Core Engine</td>
                        <td class="text-secondary">Cross-Platform .NET 8 Runtime environment</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-lg-6">
        <div class="main-container h-100">
            <h2 class="h4 mb-3 border-bottom pb-2 text-primary">Live API Data</h2>
            <p>
                For Phase 2, we updated our website to pull live content from a third-party service. To match our gaming theme, <strong>OASIS</strong>, we connected the application to the free <strong>FreeToGame API database</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Instead of using basic browser scripts, our backend code securely requests information directly from the gaming database. It safely reads the incoming data, translates it into memory, and instantly updates the template with a fresh game picture and description.
            </p>

            <h3 class="h6 mt-4 mb-2 text-uppercase font-weight-bold text-muted small">How It Works</h3>
            <table class="table table-sm mt-2 table-borderless">
                <tbody>
                    <tr class="border-bottom">
                        <td style="width: 35%;" class="fw-bold">Data Fetching</td>
                        <td class="text-secondary">Uses <code>HttpClient</code> to grab live data from the web</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-bottom">
                        <td class="fw-bold">Data Parsing</td>
                        <td class="text-secondary">Uses <code>System.Text.Json</code> to instantly read and map the game info</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-bottom">
                        <td class="fw-bold">Page Controls</td>
                        <td class="text-secondary">Uses server-side handlers (<code>OnGetAsync</code> / <code>OnPostAsync</code>) to load the text</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>